    There are several other ways our results could impact future work.
    Subjectivity labels would be a useful source of information when manually augmenting the lexical knowledge in a dictionary, e.g., when choosing hypernyms for senses or deciding which senses to eliminate when defining a coarse-grained sense inventory (if there is a subjective sense, at least one should be retained).
    Adding subjectivity labels to WordNet could also support automatic subjectivity analysis.
    First, the input corpus could be sense tagged and the subjectivity labels of the assigned senses could be exploited by a subjectivity recognition tool.
    Second, a number of methods for subjectivity or sentiment analysis start with a set of seed words and then search through WordNet to find other subjective words (Kamps and Marx, 2002; Yu